General
 
- Absolute referencing
    A function or variable can be absolutely referenced by placing a $ in front of it. 
    Then the expression will be defined in terms of the value of the variable or function at that given time.
    Otherwise if the internal variable or function is changed the value of the experession with the internal var or funct will also change.

User Functions

- This notation designates a Function
    f{x,y,z}=xyz
- To evaluate input the value of x, y, and z in the same format
    f{1,2,3} 
- To iterate through an array, input a vector or an array as an argument.
    If multiple arguments are arrays then they must have the same dimensions 
- Evaluate your expressions before inputing them as arguments otherwise issues might occur

Matrix

- Example
    [1,2,3;4,5,6]
    rows space by ; and columns by ,
- Where a and b are Matrix
    a*b gives element by element opperations
    a.*b gives linear algebra multiplication
- To index a matrix use A.(n,m) where n and m are rows and columns 0 indexed

Overwriting function names is possible but not recommended

Graphing

- You can define new functions and variables in the graphing input field however only the functions will be graphed, the vars will just be added to the vars window
- To graph a constant var just input it alone into the field
- A previously defined function of one variable can be entered into the graph by just typing the name of the function without anything else
    If the arguments of the function are included, then it will enter not as its own function but as a y= function
- A function of more than one varaible can be graphed if the other variable is passed as an evaluateable input
- If a function is defined in terms of variables, then changing the variables will change the function accordingly (unless absolutely referenced)
    Same for a function which is in terms of another function

Symbolic functions

- Various functions are delt with symbolically and can be later evaluated numarially
- For these functions, parameters have to be passed which will be listed in the functions index 
    If it is a diff, int, or lim, x is the default and does not have to be passed as an arg. 
- any symbols/variables defined or undefined will be treated as constants, unless it is the passed argument
